are no official laws which provide legal grounds to prosecute abortion,

sexual violence against women certainly does not go unpunished in the

Myanmar legal system. Crimes committed against women under the

provisions of Direct Order No. 50/1967 and Penal Code Chap. 42 provide

for harsh penalties for offenders. According to the Myanmar Penal Code,

crime is defined as any act which results in damage to property or a loss of freedom or life. In line with both national legislation and international

conduct, the faculty believed that the rape of women, no matter what their

age, qualifies for rape Uniform (sacred or unlawful) rape is considered

harmful to the victim and to Myanmar society because it reflects an

abuse of human dignity which represents the loss of freedom for both the

perpetrator and the victim. Rape remains widespread in areas of armed

conflicts in Myanmar. UNICEF and UNFPA, in collaboration with the

Myanmar National Committee on the Elimination of Violence against

Women (NCEVAW), and the National Solidarity and Development

Network for Women (NSDNW), collected sufficient information on rape to

reveal that 1,014 cases were reported during its study period. The collected information indicates that the perpetrators in rape cases were from

the local populace, the army and police.
